the articulation of feminism, queerness, and rights. Drawing from interviews with various feminist and queer media practitioners, participant observation at community events, and detailed analyses of a variety of media forms such as social media, electronic journals, digital filmmaking, film festivals, and dating app videos, Jia Tan captures the feminist, queer, and rights articulations that are simultaneously disruptive of and conditioned by state censorship, technological affordances, and dominant social norms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aFeminismzChina. 0aInternet and womenxPolitical aspectszChina. 0aInternet policyzChina. 0aMass media policyzChina. 0aSexual minoritiesxPolitical activityzChina. 0aSocial mediaxPolitical aspectszChina. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / General.2bisacsh  aChina.  aEmily Dickinson.  aHarriet Beecher Stowe.  aNathaniel Hawthorne.  aabolitionist efforts.  aactivism.  aantislavery.  aassemblage.  abiological diversity.  abiological hierarchies.  abotany.  acirculation.  acontrol over nature.  acultivation.  adigital.  afeminist.  agardening practices.  ahorticulture.  aliberalism.  aliterary abolitionists.  amasquerade.  amedia.  aplant agency.  aplant sentience.  aqueer.  arights.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Englishz978311131926108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023z9783111318806oZDB-23-DSL40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479811861.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479811861423Coveruhttps://www.degr